# Filtering in Excel

## Overview
This section demonstrates how to filter data in Excel to extract specific information based on conditions. Filtering helps in narrowing down large datasets to focus only on relevant records.

---

## Dataset
The dataset consists of:
- Student names
- Marks in Physics, Chemistry, and Mathematics
- Total marks (calculated using relative referencing)
- Percentage (calculated using cell referencing)

---

## Tasks Performed

### 1. Filtering Based on Percentage
- Applied filter on the "Percentage" column
- Used Number Filters → Greater Than or Equal To → 90
- Extracted students who scored 90% and above

---

### 2. Filtering Top Performers
- Applied filter on "Percentage" column
- Used Top 10 Filters → Top 3
- Displayed top 3 students based on percentage

---

### 3. Filtering Based on Subject Marks
- Applied filter on "Mathematics" column
- Used Number Filters → Greater Than or Equal To → 90
- Extracted students scoring high in Mathematics

---

## Key Learnings
- Understanding how filtering works on tabular data
- Applying numerical conditions to extract specific records
- Using Top N filtering to identify best performers
- Difference between sorting and filtering

---

## Notes
- Data was first converted into a table before applying filters
- Filtering does not modify the original dataset, it only displays selected rows
- Screenshots are included to show the filtering results
